Class TILDA__KEY

  • java.lang.Object
    • tilda.data._Tilda.TILDA__KEY
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    CSVable, JSONable, OCCObject, ReaderObject, WriterObject
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Key_Data
    public abstract class TILDA__KEY
extends java.lang.Object
implements WriterObject, OCCObject, JSONable, CSVable

    Key    details    top

    The Table TILDA.Key :
    • Is mapped to the generated Java 8/PostgreSQL Tilda classes Key_Factory, Key_Data in the package tilda.data.
    • Is configured for normal read/write access.
    • Is OCC-enabled. Default created/lastUpdated/deleted columns have been automatically generated.
    • Has the following identities:
      • Primary Key: refnum
      • Unique Index: name
    • Has the following index:
      • name asc (Application-side Only)
    Description:
    The table to keep track of unique keys across distributed objects/tables

    This Table contains the following columns:
     Name  TypeNullableModeInvariantProtectTZDescription
    1   refnum   long / bigint   ☐   -   ☑   -   -   The primary key for this record
    2   name   String / varchar(128)   ☐   -   ☑   -   -   The name of the table/object tracked
    3   max   long / bigint   ☐   -   ☐   -   -   The pre-allocated max RefNum for this table/object.
    4   count   int / integer   ☐   -   ☐   -   -   The size of the pre-allocation required by this table/object.
    5   created   ZonedDateTime / timestamptz   ☐   AUTO   ☑   -   -   The timestamp for when the record was created.
    6   createdETL   ZonedDateTime / timestamptz   ☑   CALCULATED   ☐   -   -   The timestamp for when the record was ETL-created.
    7   lastUpdated   ZonedDateTime / timestamptz   ☐   AUTO   ☐   -   -   The timestamp for when the record was last updated.
    8   lastUpdatedETL   ZonedDateTime / timestamptz   ☑   CALCULATED   ☐   -   -   The timestamp for when the record was last ETL-updated.
    9   deleted   ZonedDateTime / timestamptz   ☑   -   ☐   -   -   The timestamp for when the record was deleted.

      • write

        public final boolean write​(Connection C)
                    throws java.lang.Exception
        Writes the object to the data store if any changes has occurred since the object was initially read from the data store or last written. If the object was deserialized (i.e., not created via the factory lookup() or create() methods, then this method assumes a create() and will check that all non-null columns have been provided. If you need more flexibility for an upsert, use the upsert(Connection, boolean) version of write which will try a combination of insert/update to get the object to the DB. Note that if you use write() right after a create, lookup or deserialization initialization, only the template fields (not null, natural identity and/or any field set prior to calling this method) exist in memory. Call refresh() to force a select and retrieve all the fields for that record.
        Specified by:
        write in interface WriterObject
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception

      • upsert

        public final boolean upsert​(Connection C,
                            boolean updateFirst)
                     throws java.lang.Exception
        Writes the object to the data store using an upsert approach and assumes the object is either in create or deserialized mode. The parameter createFirst controls whether the logic should do an insert first and if it fails, then do an update, or the opposite (update first and if it fails, then an insert). This is necessary for databases without a robust upsert SQL syntax where separate insert/update statements must be issued. The method will figure out based on the fields set which natural identity (a unique index) is applicable for the lookup operation. Note that when you use upsert() (right after a create or deserialization initialization), only the template fields (not null, natural identity and/or any field set prior to calling this method) exist in memory. Call refresh() to force a select and retrieve all the fields for that record.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception

      • getFirstValidLookupBy

        protected int getFirstValidLookupBy()
                             throws java.lang.Exception
        Returns the first satisfied natural identify (i.e., unique indices), or if defined, the PK. by 'satisfied', we mean an identity whose columns have all been provided (i.e., not null). We prioritize natural identities over the PK since PKs are typically not stable across systems. For example, one might model a user with a PK but also an identify over an email address for example. That email address for a given logical user should be constant across multiple environments (e.g., a dev, staging or prod), where as a PK might be generated based on dynamic factors that are very likely to be different across systems.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception
